                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                       <locus from="3ra" to="34vb"/>
                        <seg type="script">Seventeenth-century script, probably
                          the first half.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black</seg>
                        <desc>Careful but irregular, poorly executed; by a poorly trained scribe. Broad, broadly spaced script.
                           The downstrokes are slanted in an unusual way. Many
                          letters are left-sloping, such ለ, በ, ቀ, ተ, ክ, ሐ, ዐ, ጸ, ጵ etc., and
                          aligned together with ይ and ደ, the characters of the Ethiopic
                          alphabet that are normally left-sloping.
                          The left-sloping signs contrast to the right-sloping
                          of መ, ማ, ም, ሣ, ሥ, ረ, ፈ, ነ, ወ, ዎ, and to the handwriting of the rubricator <ref target="#h2">Hand 2</ref>).
                          The tops of the letters are inclined to the left,
                          but poorly aligned. Rounded letter shapes. Numeral <foreign xml:lang="gez">፮</foreign>
                         looks like numeral <foreign xml:lang="gez">፯</foreign> with short stem.</desc>
                           </handNote>

                           <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic" corresp="#ms_i1.24 #ms_i1.25 #ms_i1.26 #ms_i1.27
                             #ms_i1.28 #ms_i1.29 #ms_i1.30 #ms_i1.31 #ms_i.3 #ms_i.4 #coloph1 #coloph2">
                              <seg type="script">Seventeenth-century script, probably the first half.</seg>
                                <seg type="ink">Black; red.</seg>
                                <seg type="rubrication">Divine names; incipits of the texts;
                                   miracle numbers; elements of the punctuation marks (seldom, not
                                   consequently). Rubrication has been executed
                                 along with the copying of the text. The same hand carried out rubrication
                                on <locus from="1r" to="34v"/> where the text is written by <ref target="#h1">Hand 1</ref>.</seg>
                                <persName role="scribe" ref="PRS13119FequraIyasus">Fǝqura ʾIyasus
                                of Dangʷalo (according to <ref target="#coloph1"/>) or of Qǝfrǝyā
                                 “one of the districts of Dangalo” (according to <ref target="#coloph2"/>).</persName>
                                 <desc>Careful, regular; by a trained scribe who was much more skilled
                                   than <ref target="#h1">Hand 1</ref>. Slender, right sloping script. The tops are slightly inclined to the left.
                                    At a closer look the differences between
                                   <ref target="#h1">Hand 1</ref> and <ref target="#h2">Hand 2</ref> on one hand, and
                                   between <ref target="#h2">Hand 2</ref> and <ref target="#h3">Hand 3</ref> do not appear
                                   very significant (s. below).
                                 Numeral <foreign xml:lang="gez">፮</foreign>
                                 looks like numeral <foreign xml:lang="gez">፯</foreign> with short stem. </desc>
                     </handNote>

                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic" corresp="ms_i2">
                       <locus from="44ra" to="60vb"/>
                          <seg type="script">Seventeenth-century script, probably the first half.</seg>
                          <seg type="ink">Black; red.</seg>
                          <seg type="rubrication">Incipit of <ref target="#ms_i2"/>;
                             name of John the Baptist. Rubrication has been executed
                           along with the copying of the text.</seg>
                           <desc>Careful, regular; by a trained scribe. Slender, unright or slightly right
                             sloping script. Slightly divergent downstrokes, horizontal tops. Rounded letter shapes
                             Similar to <ref target="#h2">Hand 2</ref>.
                           </desc>
                           </handNote>

                         <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic" corresp="#ms_i1.32 #ms_i1.33">
